					<description><![CDATA[<p>Neo Emerges From Stealth With Major Cybersecurity Funding Neo has raised $100 million to protect organisations against AI agents and autonomous software security threats. The Boston-based cybersecurity company announced the</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/neo-raises-100m-agentic-software-security-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal">Neo Raises $100M To Secure AI-Powered Enterprise Software</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Neo Emerges From Stealth With Major Cybersecurity Funding</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Neo has raised $100 million to protect organisations against AI agents and autonomous software security threats. The Boston-based cybersecurity company announced the funding to help enterprises secure growing numbers of software entities. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Andreessen Horowitz and Bessemer Venture Partners led the investment alongside Craft Ventures and Merlin Ventures. Neo will use the proceeds to scale operations and strengthen its cybersecurity product offerings for enterprises. </span></p>
<h2><b>Platform Brings Control To Enterprise AI Adoption</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company also plans to rapidly expand engineering and sales teams as enterprise AI adoption accelerates globally. Founded by cybersecurity veterans from SentinelOne, Wiz and Palo Alto Networks, Neo has developed what it describes as an Agentic Software Control platform. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The system enables security operations teams to monitor, manage and govern AI agents, AI-enabled applications, browsers, enterprise identities and traditional software that has gained autonomous capabilities.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">According to the company, enterprise software is evolving rapidly as AI allows applications to reason, invoke tools and perform tasks independently. Neo believes existing security platforms were not designed to manage this new generation of intelligent software.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Chief Executive Officer Nick Warner said organisations require a real-time control layer that helps them understand how AI-powered applications behave while allowing businesses to adopt new technologies securely without slowing innovation.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The platform includes a continuously updated software inventory, capability and risk analysis, real-time attribution, policy enforcement and native security controls designed specifically for agentic software environments.</span></p>
<h2><b>AI Agents Create New Security Challenges<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_203647" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203647" class="size-full wp-image-203647" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/a-futuristic-poster-showcases-a-vibrant-_uujL7TgkUKqhAA7Xb7jbYA_gJZYfAfORHuQS4rh617QBQ.png" alt="A neon futuristic visual showing AI agents interacting across systems with cybersecurity monitoring layers." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-203647" class="wp-caption-text">Neo enables enterprises to monitor and govern autonomous AI agents as security risks evolve. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Neo argues that enterprise security teams are facing a rapidly changing threat landscape as employees adopt AI tools and software providers </span><a href="https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/embed" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">embed</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> autonomous capabilities into existing business applications.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">As opposed to old-school software, AI agents operate autonomously, retain user access rights, and jump between applications, allowing them to perform actions that are opaque to typical security monitoring tools. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The vendor reports research that predicted agent-based capabilities will proliferate within the enterprise software industry over the next few years, making visibility and governance more crucial than ever. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The firm&#8217;s Neoverse knowledge base actively examines the functions, risks, and operations of applications, enabling customers to grasp which AI-enhanced applications have been given access and to determine if their set up is secure.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: <a href="https://ventureburn.com/raghu-vamsi-aerospace-group-raises-40m-manufacturing-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Raghu Vamsi Aerospace Group raises $40M to expand aerospace manufacturing</a></span></p>
<h2><b>Investors See Emerging Enterprise Security Opportunity</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Andreessen Horowitz General Partner Zane Lackey said organisations require greater visibility into AI-powered software as employees increasingly adopt autonomous tools and vendors integrate agentic capabilities into existing enterprise applications.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">“Neo combines a unique approach to AI security with an experienced enterprise cybersecurity leadership team,” Bessemer said. “The leadership team has a proven history of building and scaling successful enterprise cybersecurity platforms globally,” it added. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The founding team brings decades of combined cybersecurity experience from SentinelOne, Cylance, McAfee, and Forcepoint. The team also includes experience gained through service in Israel’s Unit 8200.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">With fresh funding in place, Neo plans to expand its platform while helping enterprises adopt AI technologies with stronger governance, real-time visibility and policy enforcement as autonomous software becomes a standard part of business operations.</span></p>
